description: Please join us for lunch from Merey as Becca talks us through her research and experience!  Genetic evidence supports that the polarity protein, partitioning defective 1c (Par1c), also known as microtubule affinity regulating kinase 1 (MARK1), functions in higher level cognition. Single nucleotide polymorphisms (SNPs) in MARK1 have been associated with autism spectrum disorder (ASD) and bipolar disorder. Furthermore, MARK1 is highly expressed in forebrain pyramidal neurons and exhibits human-specific accelerated evolution, suggesting its importance in the development of cognition. Par1c mediates synaptic plasticity in vitro through phosphorylation of PSD95. However, whether Par1c is required for the induction or maintenance of synaptic plasticity remains unknown. Here, I will discuss my work developing a novel, synaptic-targeted photoactivatable Par1c (paPar1c). Future studies will use paPar1c to determine if synaptic plasticity induction requires Par1c activation.
name: NeuroConnections Seminar - Rebecca Shear

description: We have been waiting for you! Yes - you!    GirlTREK is the largest health movement for Black women and girls and we seek to inspire women across college campuses to walk as an act of Joy & Justice. We are excited to have you join us as we walk in sisterhood for better health. With each step forward we are changing the trajectory of the health of Black women.    GirlTREK’s collaboration with Rutgers University is expected to get young women walking to better health across your college campus. We can not wait to have you join 1.2 million women across the world walking to save their lives'. We hope that you take the radical step towards a healthier future with GirlTREK today!   We will be hosting 2 walks in October. Please see the dates and times below for each walk: - Thursday, October 3rd from 4-5pm - begin at front entrance of Douglass Student Center - Friday, October 4th from 8:30-9:30am - begin at front entrance of Douglass Student Center   We'd love to stay in touch with you! Please feel free to reach out to our National College Campus Recruiter if you have questions. Feel free to email us at nyra@girltrek.org.    This event is organized in collaboration with GirlTrek, and Rutgers University partners including but not limited to Department of Landscape Architecture - SEBS, Bloustein School of Planning and Public Policy, Douglass Residential College, the Center for Social Justice Education and LGBT Communities, Paul Robeson Cultural Center, and the Institute for the Study of Global Racial Justice.

description: Scarlet Game Jam is a biannual game jam hosted by the Creation of Games Society at Rutgers University. Similar to any other game jam, participants will be given one week(ish) to design and code a game to show off at the end of the jam. At the beginning of each Scarlet Game Jam, we will also be unveiling the (optional) theme to inspire or challenge our participants, which changes with every Scarlet Game Jam, so each year is a new experience! Programmers, musicians, and artists are welcome, but no experience is necessary! Check out our website for more information: (TBD). This time around, the game jam is 2 weeks long to give everyone extra time to work on their games! Feel free to take the whole 2 weeks, one week, or even a single day to work on your game. Join the COGS Discord here! Any announcements about the jam will be blasted here: https://cogs.club/discord Make sure to sign up on our website to ensure free food for the in-person closing ceremony on April 14th. Schedule: TBD
